276
00:25:08,918 --> 00:25:13,001
And so hopefully that gives you a taste of some of our game prototypes.

277
00:25:13,801 --> 00:25:17,764
Here I will share a brief reflection on co-design.

278
00:25:19,001 --> 00:25:25,523
First off, for collaborative co-design, there is a real lift with cross-training for everyone.

279
00:25:26,503 --> 00:25:31,564
Some of this we anticipated ahead of time, for example, for our game designers getting

280
00:25:31,624 --> 00:25:36,765
more formal background on aphasia, and others we had to incorporate along the way.

281
00:25:37,806 --> 00:25:42,807
We found that both our speech-language pathologists and team members with aphasia could benefit

282
00:25:43,067 --> 00:25:46,488
from more background on the game design process itself.

283
00:25:47,421 --> 00:25:51,903
What to expect, how to give clear, actionable feedback, and all of that.

284
00:25:52,883 --> 00:26:00,346
We ended up holding a separate, accessible training session for all non-professional game designers, which helped with future workshops.

285
00:26:01,947 --> 00:26:02,607
Another takeaway.

286
00:26:03,135 --> 00:26:10,502
was around the impact of small decisions from a design perspective having big implications for

287
00:26:10,582 --> 00:26:16,567
the ultimate therapeutic status of a particular game. We had a speech-language pathologist who

288
00:26:16,587 --> 00:26:21,231
could help actively guide in making therapeutically motivated choices,

289
00:26:21,852 --> 00:26:26,115
but we found we really needed even more detailed back and forth.

290
00:26:26,909 --> 00:26:33,132
For example, in the audition game, where a player improvises lines based on card prompts,

291
00:26:33,512 --> 00:26:39,274
the choice of what counts as a line has real stakes for who can play in the actor role,

292
00:26:39,895 --> 00:26:45,557
and the choice also changes what skills and abilities are being targeted for improvement.

293
00:26:46,798 --> 00:26:53,841
And lastly, we learned some things about game design-specific adaptations to make the process more accessible.

294
00:26:54,460 --> 00:26:59,804
We already talked about the general adaptations we used to support our team members with aphasia.

295
00:27:00,684 --> 00:27:06,868
We also found that there were specific activities in game design that needed their own attention

296
00:27:07,288 --> 00:27:12,772
to make sure everyone could fully participate. A lot of this was around playtesting games at

297
00:27:12,812 --> 00:27:19,876
various stages of development. Two most useful techniques were the liberal use of visual aids

298
00:27:20,176 --> 00:27:22,498
and example turn demonstrations.

299
00:27:23,132 --> 00:27:28,215
even for ideas that were in really early stages or in flux.

300
00:27:29,255 --> 00:27:31,036
So some of the suggestions that we got

301
00:27:31,156 --> 00:27:33,117
from our team members with aphasia

302
00:27:33,277 --> 00:27:35,958
also directly shaped the rule explanations

303
00:27:36,138 --> 00:27:37,699
that we drafted for our prototypes.

304
00:27:42,521 --> 00:27:43,882
Results from this effort.

305
00:27:44,402 --> 00:27:48,024
We have three free publicly available game prototypes

306
00:27:48,304 --> 00:27:49,204
that you can check out

307
00:27:49,404 --> 00:27:51,725
along with illustrated game instructions.

308
00:27:52,364 --> 00:27:58,925
We have a website with more details on where people can sign up for playtesting or to follow along.

309
00:27:59,906 --> 00:28:07,467
We also have some great game recommendations offered as videos by our team members with Aphasia, based on what they like to play.

310
00:28:08,347 --> 00:28:12,268
And some of them have also started designing their own games outside of this collaboration.

311
00:28:13,268 --> 00:28:18,529
Lastly, you can also find some training materials and more background info.

312
00:28:22,027 --> 00:28:24,491
We're proud of this work, but it's a start.

313
00:28:25,172 --> 00:28:32,542
We plan to do more playtesting with aphasia support groups to iterate on these games.

314
00:28:34,224 --> 00:28:37,028
These games are based on therapeutic ideas.

315
00:28:37,659 --> 00:28:43,502
Actually proving therapeutic effectiveness is a much higher bar, and they need to be evaluated

316
00:28:43,562 --> 00:28:49,546
through rigorous clinical trials research in order to meet it. We're looking into funding sources to

317
00:28:49,626 --> 00:28:55,190
print and distribute these games beyond the free downloads that are available today, and we're

318
00:28:55,210 --> 00:29:00,573
thinking of ways to help out gaming communities that exist already in aphasia support groups.

319
00:29:01,434 --> 00:29:02,214
Takeaways for you.

320
00:29:03,138 --> 00:29:10,021
This is a brief window into one project around Games for Health that was made through collaborative co-design.

321
00:29:10,041 --> 00:29:20,466
So more generally, there is a growing interest and real momentum in many areas that are looking to game design as a potential form of community-driven care.

322
00:29:20,486 --> 00:29:26,548
And with the right collaboration, you as a game designer can use your skills to contribute.

323
00:29:27,768 --> 00:29:33,134
If you'd like to learn more about this particular project, check out aphasiagamesforhealth.com.

324
00:29:35,357 --> 00:29:38,741
Big shout out to the many people involved along the way.

325
00:29:41,384 --> 00:29:42,786
Thanks and see you later.

